ce:section.ce:para:
In order to investigate the catalytic performance of CuFe2O4-CDs, we have selected the reduction of 4-NP by excess amount of NaBH4 as a model reaction. As displayed in Fig. 2A, 4-NP has an absorption peak at 318 nm and shifts to 400 nm after adding NaBH4, which indicating that the formation of 4-nitrophenolate ions under alkaline condition [27]. In addition, the absorption peak intensity at 400 nm remains unchanged even after 1 h in the absence of catalyst. However, after the addition of the CuFe2O4-CDs, the peak intensity at 400 nm decreases rapidly within 30 s and a new peak rises at 302 nm (Fig. 2B). Simultaneously, the color of the solution changes quickly to colourless. These phenomena indicate that 4-NP was successfully converted to 4-aminophenol (4-AP) and the conversion rate was as high as 99% in 30 s. On the other hand, the toxic effect of NaBH4 was also reduced during the reaction because the reaction produces less toxic sodium metaborate (NaBO2) (Scheme 1
                     ) [28]. Moreover, the concentration of NaBH4 in this reaction system far exceeds that of 4-NP to ensure that the reaction conforms to pseudo first-order kinetics [29]. So the kinetic equation for this reaction can be described as ln(A/A0) = ln(C/C0) = kt, in which A and A0 are the absorbance 4-nitrophenolate ion at time t and the time of initial absorbance, respectively. The rate constant k values of CuFe2O4-CDs was calculated to be 0.152 s−1, which exhibited higher catalytic activity than CuFe2O4 and other reported nanocatalysts in this reduction process (Table S1 and Fig. 2C). Based on the experimental results and previous reports [30,31], the mechanism of catalytic reduction of 4-NP is proposed. After both NaBH4 and 4-NP are adsorbed on the CuFe2O4-CDs surface, the CuFe2O4-CDs act as a medium to facilitate electron relay from the donor BH4
                     − to the acceptor 4-nitrophenolate ions. At the same time, the hydride forms hydrogen atom and then attacks 4-nitrophenolate ions, thereby reducing 4-NP to 4-AP. From Table S2, the presence of CDs makes the organic content of CuFe2O4-CDs higher than that of CuFe2O4. Since CDs do not have catalytic activity, the pure CuFe2O4 sample contains more catalytic active substances than CuFe2O4-CDs in the catalytic process. However, the CuFe2O4-CDs nanocomposite showed higher catalytic activity than pure CuFe2O4 particles. The possible reason is that the CuFe2O4 nanocrystalline particle size present in the CuFe2O4-CDs is smaller than that of the pure CuFe2O4 sample, so that the CuFe2O4-CDs have a larger active surface area to absorb 4-NP and NaBH4, which eventually leads to enhanced catalytic ability. The reusability of CuFe2O4-CDs was studied and shown in Fig. S6. After recycling five times, the CuFe2O4-CDs has a conversion rate of 50% within 106 s, while the catalytic time of CuFe2O4 was as high as 250 s at the same conversion rate (Fig. 2D). This result indicates that CuFe2O4-CDs possess better catalytic stability due to the presence of the CDs layer.
